<div align="justify">
<h1>welcome note</h1>
<p>I am a PhD
candidate at the <a href="http://www.linguistics.ucla.edu/" target="_blank">UCLA
Linguistics
Department</a>. Before coming to UCLA, I studied linguistics
at the <a href="http://il.rsuh.ru/section.html?id=6064" target="_blank">Russian
State University for the Humanities</a> in
Moscow, from where I graduated in 2009 with an equivalent of Master's
degree.</p>

<p>My main research interests are formal semantics, formal pragmatics, and cross-linguistic variation within these domains and sources thereof. I always keep an eay on the cross-linguistic perspective even when not using primary data. This provides a more balanced picture. The empirical phenomena I study from this angle are evidentiality, attitude predicates, modality and parenthesis. In addition to a more general typological perspective, I am also interested in micro-variation in geographically and/or genetically related languages. I have done fieldwork on a variety of languages (Altaic, Kartvelian, Northwest Caucasian, Quechua, Slavic) and am interested in fieldwork methodologies, especially in semantics, and in language documentation. Most of my recent work is

</p>

<p>My dissertation is on the interaction of evidentials and attitudes
across languages. For more information, see my <a href="http://linguistics.ucla.edu/people/grads/korotkova/files/self/papers/prospectus.pdf" target="_blank">dissertation prospectus</a> and the corresponding section <a href="http://www.linguistics.ucla.edu/people/grads/korotkova/research.html" target="_blank">here</a>. I am also interested in the
typology of wh-scope marking and similar-looking phenomena in
Slavic. Over the years, I have also worked on the Adyghe morphology and
tense and aspect system. I am still a part of the language
documentation project on Northwest Caucasian languages, hosted by the
Russian State University for the Humanities. Each of these projects is described in greater detail <a href="http://www.linguistics.ucla.edu/people/grads/korotkova/research.html">here</a>. The <a href="http://www.linguistics.ucla.edu/people/grads/korotkova/cv.html">CV</a> contains the full list of things I've been up to during my linguistics career.<br>
</p>

<p>Besides linguistics I do
photography
and paparazzi <a href="https://www.flickr.com/photos/57449897@N07/collections/72157644489382245/" target="_blank">the
department</a> and <a href="https://www.flickr.com/photos/57449897@N07/sets/" target="_blank">beyond</a>. Here you can find selected <a href="https://www.flickr.com/photos/57449897@N07/sets/72157644476480781/" target="_blank">places</a> and <a href="https://www.flickr.com/photos/57449897@N07/sets/72157633483152597/" target="_blank">faces</a>.</p>
</div>




<h1>recent and upcoming talks</h1>

<div align="justify">

<p>November 2014. Invited commentator at the workshop <a href="http://linguistlist.org/confservices/customhome.cfm?emeetingid=6402JA4458BE744840A050441" target="_blank"><i>Pronouns in embedded contexts
at the syntax-semantics interface</i></a>, Eberhard Karls Universität Tübingen, Germany, 7-9 November 2014.</p>

<p>October 2014. "Illocutionary evidentials: embed or not embed". To be presented at <a href="http://www.iatl.org.il/?page_id=406" target="_blank"><i>Israel Association for Theoretical Linguistics (IATL) 30</i></a>, Ben Gurion University, October 20-21, 2014. <a href="http://linguistics.ucla.edu/people/grads/korotkova/files/self/abs/iatl2014_abstract.pdf" target="_blank"><b>[abstract]</b></a></p>

<p>October 2014. "Evidential shift as indexical shift: a case study from Turkish". To be presented at the <a href="http://www.ucm.es/emel14/" target="_blank"><i>International Conference on Evidentiality and Modality in European Languages (EMEL)</i></a>, Complutense University of Madrid, Spain, 6-8 October 2014.</p>


<p>September 2014. "Some structural analogies between evidentials and indexicals". To be presented at <a href="http://www.uni-goettingen.de/en/sinn-und-bedeutung-2014/450376.html" target="_blank"><i>Sinn und Bedeutung (SuB) 19</i></a>, Georg August Universität Göttingen, Germany, 15-17 September 2014.</p>

<p>July 2014. <i>TBA</i>. Talk at the Linguistics Department at University of Konstanz.</p>


